# Greptile configuration for the Paideia repository.
# Greptile reads this file to understand repo-specific review conventions.
# See https://greptile.com/docs/configuration for the full schema.

review:
  # Advisory mode: post review comments on every PR, but do not block merge.
  # Flip to `blocking` once the signal quality is trusted.
  mode: advisory

  # Severity floor for posted comments. Greptile deduplicates and suppresses
  # below this level to avoid nit-comment noise.
  minimum_severity: medium

  # Focus reviewer attention on areas where bugs and prompt drift matter most.
  focus_paths:
    - src/lib/essay-generator.ts     # load-bearing prompt logic; wording changes alter output
    - src/lib/providers/             # LLM provider abstraction; API contracts
    - src/app/api/portal/generate/   # main generation route orchestration
    - scripts/qa-generation.ts       # QA harness — prompt/scoring correctness matters
    - scripts/qa-lib/                # elite threshold logic
    - src/__tests__/                 # test coverage should not silently drop

  # Paths that produce noise without real review value.
  ignore_paths:
    - node_modules/
    - .next/
    - .vercel/
    - output/qa/                     # QA report fixtures; not source code
    - scripts/fixtures/              # test fixtures; not source code
    - prisma/migrations/             # autogenerated
    - "*.lock"
    - "package-lock.json"

repository_context:
  # Project-specific conventions Greptile should weight heavily.
  conventions: |
    This is a Next.js 16 app that generates student-voice essays via a
    12-pass Level 2 pipeline. Key review priorities:

    1. Prompt wording in src/lib/essay-generator.ts is load-bearing — a
       one-word change in a system prompt can materially alter generated
       output. Flag any prompt edit and ask whether QA was re-run to confirm
       no elite-bar regression (see docs/superpowers/specs/2026-04-16-level2-
       refinement-design.md for the elite bar).

    2. The LLM provider abstraction at src/lib/providers/ is multi-provider.
       Any new call site must go through getProvider(), not the Anthropic or
       Gemini SDKs directly. Runtime code must not call Anthropic
       (the user has moved off Anthropic entirely — Anthropic code is kept
       as dormant insurance only).

    3. Silent failures are unacceptable. `try { ... } catch {}` with no
       logging, no rethrow, and no fallback behavior is a bug. Stream
       generation errors must surface to the client, not hang.

    4. New env vars must be documented in .env.example or they will break
       production deploys silently.

    5. QA scripts under scripts/qa-lib/ enforce numeric quality floors;
       don't widen thresholds casually. Lowering a floor requires a
       justification comment in the diff.

    6. Tests live in src/__tests__/ and run via vitest. New code that
       touches prompt construction, provider wiring, or QA scoring should
       have test coverage.

  tech_stack:
    - Next.js 16 (App Router)
    - TypeScript strict mode
    - Prisma 7 / PostgreSQL (Neon)
    - Gemini via @google/genai
    - Together AI (Level 1: DeepSeek / Kimi)
    - NextAuth
    - Vercel Blob
